    "150717906": {
      "title": "Phenomenology, ethnomethodology, and family discourse",
      "abstract": "Conventional approaches to family studies typically begin with an understanding or definition of the family that specifies its characteristics as a particular kind of group. This seems eminently reasonable, both commonsensically and as a social scientific practice. We all believe families to inhabit everyday life as concrete entities, and to study them we must clearly designate what is being observed. But how is the student of the family to take his or her encounters with people in the \u201creal world\u201d whose images of family seem radically different from the academic definitions? Consider, for example, the now-familiar refrain of the athlete who explains his team\u2019s success by noting that \u201cWe have a good family atmosphere going\u201d (Gubrium & Holstein, 1990, p. 140). Or what do we make of urban anthropologist Carol Stack\u2019s (1974, p. 58) report that in the community she studied, \u201cWhen friends more than adequately share the exchange of goods and services, they are called kinsmen \u2026 if two women of the same age are helping one another, they call their friend \u2018just a sister\u2019\u201d?"
    }
  }
}